"His biggest quality is his consistency. He turns up every week, and even when we've had some poor performances and even when some individuals within the side have played poorly, Julian's contribution has always been absolutely first rate," added Baxter.
"He's virtually always our top tackler, virtually always our top clearout guy, and probably the thing that people don't appreciate about him is how important he is to our attack.
"A lot of people talk about open-sides as being tacklers and defenders and disruptive people, but Julian is very important to our attack because he clears so many breakdowns."

SSI has halted operations at its Redcar blast furnace, citing declining market demand and escalating operating expenses. This facility, a workplace for nearly 2,000 individuals, was acquired by SSI in 2010 after its former owner, Tata Steel, had placed it into an inactive state. Ms. Soubry clarified that government assistance for British steel production is restricted by European Union regulations, preventing direct financial intervention. Cornelius Louwrens, SSI UK's Business Director, conveyed profound regret for this decision, yet stressed its "absolute necessity" given the challenging market conditions. He underscored that this step is intended to safeguard the business's enduring viability, with all potential avenues for the site currently being explored. The future of the Redcar plant, a significant industrial hub in the North East, is now uncertain, creating significant apprehension among its approximately 2,000 workers and the wider supply chain. Trade unions have urged immediate government intervention, asserting that a complete cessation of operations would critically damage the regional economy and the UK's industrial base. Despite Ms. Soubry's remarks regarding EU limitations, government officials face growing demands to devise a strategy for preserving the acclaimed steel production site. The company had previously drawn attention to the detrimental effect of cheap imports and elevated energy costs, persistent challenges within the British steel industry. As one of Europe's largest, this blast furnace is vital to the integrated steelworks, and its cessation effectively halts all primary steel manufacturing at the location. The local populace, still recuperating from prior closures during Tata Steel's tenure, observes with apprehension as Redcar's fate remains uncertain, emphasizing the pervasive difficulties confronting heavy industry across the UK.

Initially, Queen's Lodge in Colwyn Bay served as the prominent home of the inaugural Lord Colwyn. After the passing of notable industrialist and banker Frederick Henry Smith in 1946, the estate was transformed into a pair of distinct care facilities. Locally, these institutions were commonly known as 'the lodge', operating for numerous decades. Management was later assumed by the Merseyside Hospitals Council, a change reflecting the substantial post-war shifts in Welsh healthcare services. Ultimately, the sprawling property stopped operating as care facilities, prompting various suggestions for its future applications in later years. Its deep historical and architectural significance, especially its transformation from a stately private residence into multiple care establishments following Smith's death, is thoroughly documented by the National Monuments Record of Wales. This crucial archive meticulously safeguards a complete history of the lodge and its changing importance within the Colwyn Bay area.

Former WBA super-bantamweight champion Scott Quigg is on the verge of advancing significantly towards a highly anticipated clash with Welshman Lee Selby, contingent on a win this Saturday. Quigg described this as a "massive opportunity" he has "diligently pursued," acknowledging Selby's status as a "premier competitor." He believes triumphing over Selby would reignite his world title aspirations.

Nonetheless, Quigg stressed his complete focus on the immediate contest, asserting he must not underestimate his opponent, as every bout serves as a crucial step forward. He confirmed his preparedness for any challenge his adversary presents.

Promoter Eddie Hearn has long envisioned a major domestic showdown between Quigg and Selby, confident it would be a substantial draw for British boxing enthusiasts. Hearn highlighted the exceptional talents and large fan followings of both Scott and Lee, adding that the public demands these prominent matchups. He stated that a strong performance from Quigg this Saturday would lead to a vigorous pursuit of that bout, calling it an exciting prospect for Wales and the entire British boxing community.

Quigg echoed Hearn's sentiments, affirming his readiness. He expressed certainty in securing a victory this Saturday, after which serious dialogue concerning Lee can truly commence. His ambition is to engage in the most impactful fights, and a contest against Selby is certainly among them.

The 33-year-old forward began his career with Northampton, before spells with Mansfield, Lincoln and Chester.
He then scored 10 goals in 39 league games for Shrewsbury and secured a ¬£50,000 move to French side Nice, but joined Hamilton two years later.
The forward has since played in Bulgaria and most recently has been plying his trade in South Korea.
Asamoah, who will wear the number 25 shirt for Carlisle, has made four appearances for Ghana, scoring one goal.

The civil liberties organization, Liberty, has been a prominent detractor of the Investigatory Powers Act, lambasting its provisions as an "assault on our freedom" because they enable widespread governmental surveillance. This legislation, enacted in November and disparagingly known as the 'Snooper's Charter' by its opponents, grants extensive monitoring capabilities to security agencies like MI5, MI6, and GCHQ. According to Martha Spurrier, Liberty's director, the Act facilitates the indiscriminate collection of personal data from ordinary citizens, establishing a perilous precedent for civil liberties rather than precisely targeting genuine threats. She considers this among the most extreme surveillance laws implemented in democratic nations.

The powers sanctioned by the Act encompass gathering vast amounts of information from digital devices, the ability to remotely control or alter them, intercepting electronic communications such as texts, online messages, and emails, monitoring phone conversations, and tracking individuals' physical whereabouts. Furthermore, it mandates that internet service providers store users' web browsing histories for a full year. Despite significant opposition, including calls from the House of Lords for enhanced privacy safeguards, the government, then under Prime Prime Minister Theresa May, successfully enacted the bill. May contended that the Act was vital for national security in the digital age, asserting it merely updated existing authority while improving accountability and transparency through independent judicial oversight.

Nonetheless, Liberty, along with other privacy advocates, continues to question the Act's proportionality. They highlight concerns regarding mass data collection, unauthorized access to devices, and the compulsory year-long retention of browsing histories as unacceptable encroachments on personal privacy. Upcoming legal challenges, potentially escalating to the European Court of Human Rights, underscore the fundamental tension between the state's security imperatives and individual freedoms, with critics warning of a chilling effect on free expression.

The 26-year-old, a former midfielder for SC Amiens, Rayo Vallecano, and Dijon, exhibits impressive versatility. He can skillfully operate as a defensive anchor or in a more attacking, creative capacity. Drawing on considerable experience from France and Spain, he's now reportedly attracting interest from English clubs like MK Dons, as he seeks a fresh professional opportunity. His past involvement with these demanding teams underlines his top-tier experience.

Thomas Groome, 53, vanished from Thorne, Doncaster, on January 1, 2010, the last time his family saw him. His sudden disappearance prompted an extensive three-year investigation by South Yorkshire Police. Despite wide-ranging searches, Mr. Groome's body was never recovered, a profoundly upsetting detail that proved central to the subsequent legal process.

Jason Thaxter, a Hexthorpe, Doncaster resident, was eventually found guilty of murder and conspiring to obstruct a lawful burial after a five-week hearing at Sheffield Crown Court. He received a minimum prison sentence of 17 years before becoming eligible for parole. The court proceedings revealed that Thaxter had violently killed Mr. Groome and deliberately concealed his remains. While the lack of physical evidence presented significant challenges for investigators, the prosecution successfully built a compelling case against Thaxter.

At sentencing, Judge Roger Thomas QC described Thaxter's conduct as 'callous and calculated,' emphasizing the deep and lasting distress caused to Mr. Groome's family, who are still unable to provide him with a proper burial. South Yorkshire Police commended their team's persistent efforts in achieving a conviction in this challenging 'no-body' homicide investigation. Mr. Groome's relatives continue to earnestly appeal for any details concerning where his remains might be, hoping to finally bring him home and attain a degree of closure.

Profits at the technology giant were up 17% from the same period last year.
"Our devices and services transformation is progressing," said boss Steve Ballmer in a statement. He added that Microsoft is launching a "wide range" of new products in the coming quarter.
The report shed no light on who is to replace Mr Ballmer, who announced plans to retire within the next year.
The company has released several new products this quarter, including an update to Windows 8, and recently bought the mobile phone unit of struggling Finnish giant Nokia.
Shares rose 6% in after hours trading on the strong results.
For the first time, Microsoft also announced sales of its tablet computer, Surface.
It said revenues from Surface "grew to $400 million with sequential growth in revenue and units sold over the prior quarter".
Last quarter, the company was forced to take an embarrassing write down of $900m after sluggish sales.
The computer, well-liked by reviewers, marked Microsoft's first foray into hardware manufacturing.
However consumers, many of whom expressed displeasure at Microsoft's update to its popular operating system Windows, did not bite.
The company still did not provide sales figures of the device.
Investors hoping for any information about who will replace Mr Ballmer in the new year were disappointed.
Earlier today, on a conference call to discuss earnings, Ford boss Alan Mullaly declined to comment on rumours that he was being considered for the top job.
Other contenders include Stephen Elop, the former head of Nokia, who resigned as boss after Microsoft announced it would purchase the Nokia's mobile phone unit for 5.4bn euros ($7.2bn; ¬£4.6bn) in September.
Mr Elop is now head of Devices and Services at Nokia, although he is expected to transfer to Microsoft - where he was once a top manager - once the deal is completed.
Mr Ballmer has been at the helm of Microsoft since 2000, and has been at the company since 1980.

The talks come after Papua New Guinea's Supreme Court ruled the facility unconstitutional, overturning a deal reached between the governments.
Australia sends asylum seekers there under its offshore processing policy.
Papua New Guinea has now said it will close the facility, but it is not clear when that could happen.
Manus Island was first opened in 2001, and along with Australia's other offshore processing centres, has played a central role in Australia's controversial asylum policy.
Papua New Guinea's high commissioner to Australia Charles Lepani said the detainees were now Australia's responsibility, but Australia has remained opposed to taking any of them.
Immigration Minister Peter Dutton said on Thursday there was room for them at another detention centre on Nauru.
"There's capacity [on Nauru] but we're talking with the PNG government about what options are available in PNG and we'll continue those discussions with them," Mr Dutton said on Sky News.
This comes after an Iranian asylum seeker held at the Australian-funded detention centre on Nauru set himself on fire on Wednesday.
His actions were a "political protest" according to the Nauruan government.
Mr Dutton said the 23-year old man was in a serious condition and was evacuated to Australia for treatment.
Nauru is a small Pacific Island nation about 3,000 km (1,800 miles) north-east of Australia.
It was previously administered by Australia but gained independence in 1968.
What next for Manus Island asylum-seekers?
Manus Island: Australia's Guantanamo?
Australia's controversial asylum policy
Mr Dutton said that the man set himself on fire at a settlement outside the detention centre.
"He's in a very serious condition," Mr Dutton said.
"His outlook is not good at all."
He also confirmed that other asylum seekers held on the island had harmed themselves.
"What we've been very clear about is that if people come to Australia for medical assistance they'll be returning back to Nauru once that medical assistance has been provided.
"We have returned three people back to Nauru from Australia and they have returned because the medical assistance that they sought in Australia has been provided," Mr Dutton said.
Representatives from the refugee agency UNHCR were visiting Nauru when the incident occurred, he said.
An Iranian asylum seeker was last month fined for trying to kill himself during an attempt to move him and his daughter from the centre on Nauru.

The detailed terms of the agreement reveal that General Motors effectively spent as much as £6 billion to divest its Vauxhall and Opel brands. A notable portion of this sum, £750 million, was allocated not to manufacturing assets but to resolve previous loans for the Opel/Vauxhall owners. This unusual arrangement indicates GM was offloading a persistent financial burden, rather than merely disposing of an operational business. Nevertheless, the majority of the £6 billion originated from substantial pension responsibilities, which GM opted to retain instead of transferring to Peugeot. GM will continue to fund more than £5 billion in pension entitlements for former Vauxhall and Opel staff, highlighting the immense expense associated with these enduring commitments. This decision, made at GM's Detroit headquarters, emphasizes the company's strategic objective: to remove years of European losses from its financial statements that had impeded its overall performance. By holding onto these liabilities, GM circumvented potentially complex and prolonged discussions with Peugeot, thereby accelerating the deal and ensuring a decisive separation.

As a result, this deal seems less like a lucrative divestment for GM and more like an expensive withdrawal from a market where it consistently struggled. In contrast, Peugeot's takeover of Vauxhall and Opel offers a significant opportunity to enlarge its European market presence and achieve considerable economies of scale. However, it also involves acquiring a business that has reported losses for almost two decades, which will demand widespread restructuring and significant investment to achieve profitability. Peugeot's main challenge will be smoothly combining Vauxhall and Opel's operations, streamlining manufacturing, and reducing costs, all while preserving staff morale and brand perception. With Peugeot at the helm, Vauxhall will focus on sharing vehicle platforms, standardizing components, and rationalizing its product lineup to boost financial returns. This entire strategic move represents a major shift in GM's worldwide approach, allowing it to allocate its capital towards more lucrative territories such as North America and China, and to heavily fund innovative technologies like electric and autonomous vehicles. The divestiture of Vauxhall and Opel frees up funds and management attention, enabling GM to pursue global expansion prospects, despite the substantial £6 billion cost incurred for this strategic independence.

David Craig Ellis, 41, has confessed to killing Alec Warburton, 59, at a Lon Masarn home in Sketty, Swansea. Emergency crews were dispatched to the address. At Swansea Crown Court, Ellis admitted guilt to manslaughter; his sentencing remains deferred. The court was informed Mr Warburton's death followed a dispute.

Mr Mills had been deputy chairman of the group designated the lead "out" campaign by the Electoral Commission.
He has previously claimed the campaign was torn by internal feuding.
He was reported to have been on the verge of quitting in February when Labour MP Kate Hoey joined a rival out campaign.
In his resignation letter, the home shopping magnate said he had "come to believe that it would be useful and more effective for the Leave campaign if there was a strong and independent Labour voice for the arguments to leave the EU".
"I can now focus fully on my role as ... director of Labour Leave, and create that distinctive voice," he said.
"In the run up to the vote on 23 June, Labour Leave will provide a compelling and robust left-of-centre case for leaving the EU."
The vast majority of Labour MPs are in favour of Britain remaining in the EU - with about a dozen campaigning for an exit.
Labour former minister Frank Field has warned the party it risks losing "a swathe" of voters to UKIP by campaigning to remain in the EU.
Mr Mills, who played a leading role in the 1975 referendum campaign against EU membership, has also been critical of Jeremy Corbyn's decision to back staying in.
He said: "I hope this decision will be a transformative first step to motivating Labour people who are still unsure how they will vote, to vote Leave in June to secure a better, fairer future for this country.
"Labour Leave will continue to work with Vote Leave, as well as other Leave campaigns across the piece, to secure a stronger future for the UK outside the EU."
Vote Leave was the organisation chosen by the Electoral Commission to take the lead in making the case for Britain to leave the European Union. It is headed by big Conservative names Boris Johnson and Michael Gove and Labour MP Gisela Stuart with support from Lib Dem and UKIP figures, as well as business people.
Subscribe to the BBC News EU referendum email newsletter and get a weekly round-up of news, features and analysis on the campaign sent straight to your inbox.

Star Randel-Hanson killed Derick Marney, 70, at a flat in Vernon Terrace, Brighton, in May 2015.
He broke down and confessed to the murder 10 days later he went to tarot reader Jayne Braiden on Brighton seafront.
She alerted police but was told it was a "non-emergency" so she waited an hour with the killer for an officer to come.
Ms Braiden told BBC Radio 5 Live: "By the time we got to the devil card he broke down and started crying.
"It's the first time I've dealt with murder before. It was a shock but you have to be professional and I needed to keep him calm."
Mr Marney died from a six-inch (15cm) stab wound to his side, which punctured his vital organs.
Sussex Police said it was "not clear" what motivated Randel-Hanson - who was jailed for life on 9 May - to carry out the murder.
After gaining the defendant's trust, Ms Braiden asked him whether she could go outside to call the police. He agreed.
She said: "I explained [to the 999 operator] I was a tarot reader and told her a man had confessed to murder.
"She told me it was a non-priority call and I needed to ring the non-emergency number.
"Unfortunately they didn't believe me, but I'm not surprised at that."
She said she then bought Randel-Hanson a drink from a shop next door and waited 55 minutes for police to arrive.
"I asked him if it was ok if I took notes... I took names, places, where he had been stabbed and where the body was," she said.
"I didn't ask him why, and to be fair I don't think he wanted to talk to me about that.
"We joked about the time it took the police to come.
"He was getting tense at that point as I was not only looking for police through the glass doors, he was as well."
Sussex Police later admitted the call had been given the wrong level of priority.
A spokesman said it has been discussed with the call handler concerned and "suitable advice was given".

The swoon weighed on US markets, offsetting gains in financial and energy stocks.
The tech-heavy Nasdaq index fell 113.84 points or 1.80%% to 6,207.92.
The broader S&P 500 dipped 2.02 points or 0.08% to 2,431.77, while the Dow Jones edged up 89.44 points, rising 0.42% to 21,271.97.
US markets had seen limited movement earlier this week, as markets waited to see the results of the UK election and reaction to the testimony by former FBI director James Comey in Washington.
Mr Trump's firing of Mr Comey, who had been leading the FBI investigation into ties between Russia and the Trump campaign, has drawn a political backlash, threatening the prospects for key business initiatives in Washington.
But the testimony contained little new information and Republicans appeared confident in plans to press forward on key initiatives, such as loosening financial rules.
Financial stocks gained nearly 2% on Friday, while energy stocks rose more than 2% as oil prices stabilised.
But those increases couldn't overcome the fall in technology stocks.
Netflix fell 4.7%, Apple sank 3.9%, Google-owner Alphabet dropped 3.4% Facebook declined 3.3% and Amazon fell 3.2%.
The firms' weeks of success on Wall Street had won it an acronym - FAANG - and led to a steady drumbeat of commentary about possibly inflated values, but it wasn't clear what triggered the widespread sell-off.
It wasn't all bad for internet companies.
Pandora shares jumped 1.2% on Friday, after the music streaming service said it would receive a $480m cash infusion from Sirius XM.
Pandora said the investment by Sirius XM, a satellite radio company, would give it money to grow. It also gives Sirius exposure to the market for online radio.

South Yorkshire Police responded to a residential burglary in Shiregreen early last Monday morning. The resident was physically injured during the forced entry and is now hospitalized, recovering in a stable condition. The incident, which occurred just after midnight, is currently under investigation by the force. Detective Inspector Paul Wilson, leading the inquiry, described the event as deeply distressing for the homeowner. He appealed for anyone who witnessed anything unusual or suspicious in the Shiregreen area around that time to come forward, stressing that even minor details could be crucial to their investigation. Wilson affirmed the police's firm commitment to apprehending those responsible for the break-in and ensuring they face justice. Officers are conducting door-to-door interviews and meticulously reviewing local CCTV footage in their efforts to identify and arrest the offenders.

Andreea Cristea tragically became the fifth casualty of the March 22nd terrorist attack. On that fateful day, Khalid Masood deliberately drove a vehicle into pedestrians on Westminster Bridge before fatally stabbing a police officer, and was subsequently shot dead himself. Ms. Cristea, 31, a Romanian architect on holiday in London with her boyfriend, Andrei Burnaz, had been receiving critical medical care since the incident. It has since come to light that Mr. Burnaz had planned to propose to her during their trip. Her family released a statement on Thursday, confirming the passing of Ms. Cristea. The visitor was propelled into the River Thames during Khalid Masood’s rampage. Although she was rescued from the water, she sustained severe head injuries and a serious lung infection, remaining in a critical condition for weeks at St Thomas' Hospital. Her family, including her parents and sister, maintained a constant vigil at her bedside, holding onto hope for her recovery until her unfortunate demise.

Mr. Burnaz, who suffered a fractured foot in the attack and underwent surgery, has emotionally recounted the terrifying moments after they were struck and his frantic search for Andreea amidst the chaos. He described witnessing Ms. Cristea disappear into the water after being hit by the vehicle and his desperate efforts to locate her before rescuers pulled her out. The couple, originally from Constanța, Romania, was on a romantic getaway, and the revelation of Mr. Burnaz's planned proposal adds a deeply poignant layer to their story, highlighting the dreams and future abruptly snatched away by the act of terror.

Ms. Cristea's death regrettably brings the total number of direct fatalities from Khalid Masood’s assault to five. The other victims included American tourist Kurt Cochran, retired window cleaner Leslie Rhodes, and mother-of-two Aysha Frade, all of whom were struck on Westminster Bridge. Also tragically killed was PC Keith Palmer, the brave officer stabbed by Masood near the Palace of Westminster. The attack, which shocked the world, transformed a vibrant London landmark into a scene of unimaginable horror and sorrow.

Numerous tributes have honored Andreea, remembering her as a lively, gifted architect with a promising future. The Romanian Ambassador to the UK conveyed profound sorrow, expressing the shared grief of the Romanian community for her loss. Her tragic death serves as a powerful reminder of the global impact of such violence, affecting individuals from various backgrounds who were simply enjoying a day in a major capital city. The investigation into Masood’s motivations and potential associates persists, yet the devastating human cost of his actions, exemplified by Ms. Cristea and Mr. Burnaz, endures as the most moving legacy. London, a city renowned for its enduring spirit and resilience, mourns its lost but stands united against the hatred that seeks to divide it.

British heavyweight boxing champion Tyson Fury issued an apology last month after a video circulated online featuring derogatory homophobic, misogynistic, and antisemitic comments. Wladimir Klitschko, the former champion scheduled to face Fury in Manchester on July 9th, conveyed deep dismay at the remarks. The Ukrainian boxer, visibly upset, described the footage as "highly unsettling." He emphasized that professional athletes bear a crucial responsibility to be role models, asserting that leveraging one's public platform for such incendiary rhetoric—particularly antisemitic slurs that harken back to grim historical eras—is totally indefensible and fundamentally antithetical to the spirit of sport. Klitschko, whose homeland suffered profoundly in World War II, voiced serious concerns about the potential repercussions of these statements.

Fury’s controversial pronouncements ignited widespread condemnation throughout Britain, leading to calls for his boxing license to be rescinded. His antisemitic tirade, asserting that "Zionist, Jewish people... own all the banks, all the palaces, all the world," caused profound offense by echoing ancient bigotries. Moreover, prior misogynistic and homophobic comments he made resurfaced, solidifying the impression of deep-seated bias. The Campaign Against Antisemitism, a leading UK advocacy organization, was especially vocal, urging strong action against the British boxer. They highlighted the peril of prejudiced language from prominent athletes, especially when it resembles rhetoric employed by figures such as Hitler, stressing that public figures must comprehend the serious impact of their utterances. Klitschko added, "This extends beyond boxing; it’s about basic human decency and mutual respect." He pointed out that despite their impending bout, Fury's conduct had gone beyond the sport, raising grave concerns about a champion's integrity. The significant public uproar ultimately forced Fury to offer an apology, which many perceived as insincere, thus escalating the controversy even further.

By the close of play on day three, Glamorgan had reached 293 for the loss of 9 wickets, establishing a substantial lead of 260 runs. Jacques Rudolph's quest for his maiden Championship century of 2016 was cut short at 56 when he unluckily dislodged his bails.

Prior to this, Essex's first innings concluded at 319 all out. A pivotal role was played by Craig Meschede, who claimed his first five-wicket haul in first-class cricket for Glamorgan, finishing with excellent figures of 5 wickets for 84 runs. His precise seam bowling broke through Essex's middle order, notably removing significant players like Simon Harmer and Neil Wagner. Even with Alastair Cook's resilient 90 runs, Meschede's influential bowling restricted Essex's total.

Beginning their second innings 26 runs behind, Glamorgan established a solid foundation largely due to openers Nick Selman, who contributed 41, and Jacques Rudolph. Rudolph, despite his eventual dismissal, appeared composed throughout his 125-ball innings, which included seven fours. His ambition of reaching a hundred was dashed by an unlucky error, as he inadvertently deflected a Jamie Porter delivery onto his own wickets.

Following Rudolph's wicket, with the score at 110 for 2, Marnus Labuschagne added a quick 28 runs before Sam Cook trapped him leg before wicket. Glamorgan's subsequent batsmen then endured a challenging phase. Though Chris Cooke fought his way to 35 and Kiran Carlson chipped in with 22, Essex's bowlers capitalized on the unpredictable bounce of the pitch, leading to a steady fall of wickets.

A late resistance from Ryan Thomas, who was unbeaten on a valuable 18, helped stretch Glamorgan's advantage as visibility diminished. The visiting side is banking on their tail-enders to score crucial runs on the last day, aiming to set a formidable target for Essex. The wicket, already showing signs of deterioration, is expected to increasingly assist spin bowlers.

Rudolph's initial batting efforts and Meschede's controlled bowling have established a strong platform for Glamorgan; however, the concluding day is set to be full of suspense. The game remains delicately balanced, yet Glamorgan maintains an edge, supported by their sturdy batting and Meschede's impactful spell.

Upon the arrival of the Great North Air Ambulance at the 2016 Newby Cross crash site, Logan Murdoch was found unresponsive, critically injured, and no longer breathing. Tragically, two other individuals from Carlisle, 29-year-old Hayley Murdoch and 71-year-old Sheila Dixon, had already succumbed to their injuries sustained in the collision.

Years later, Dr. Laura Duffy contacted Logan, expressing profound amazement at his remarkable recovery. She distinctly recalled the accident scene near Newby Cross as one of the most demanding situations she had ever encountered. Logan was clinically deceased, yet through the prompt and coordinated efforts of first responders, paramedics, and the air ambulance crew, he was successfully resuscitated at the roadside. He was then airlifted to the Royal Victoria Infirmary in Newcastle, where his severe condition necessitated a medically induced coma for several weeks as he fought for his life. His family, already reeling from the loss of Hayley and Sheila, prepared for the worst, enduring harrowing days and nights in constant vigil by his hospital bed.

Against all odds, Logan embarked on a slow and challenging path to recovery. Dr. Duffy remembered the initial grim prognosis, which predicted severe brain damage and likely lifelong disability. However, his inherent resilience and strong will, combined with outstanding medical care, defied these bleak expectations. His extensive rehabilitation, spanning many months, encompassed physical and speech therapy, along with vital psychological support to help him process the trauma and the deep sorrow of losing his mother and grandmother. Dr. Duffy’s call powerfully underscored how close he had been to dying. She emphasized the miraculous nature of his survival, attributing it to the crucial, life-saving interventions performed during those critical moments at the crash site near Carlisle. Logan, now a dedicated advocate for the Great North Air Ambulance, frequently reflects on that pivotal day, acknowledging that without their swift intervention, he would not be alive today to share his story or cherish the memories of his beloved Hayley Murdoch and Sheila Dixon. While lasting physical and emotional scars remain, so too does an immense gratitude for the second chance at life he received.

Stefan Appleton, 18, was with friends when he was attacked in Nightingale Park in Islington on 10 June last year.
The killer stabbed him with the 25in (63cm) serrated blade after leaping off a stolen moped, the Old Bailey heard.
The 17-year-old, who cannot be named due to his age, was cleared of murder. He will be sentenced on 21 April.
Mr Appleton, a college student from Islington, had been with friends when his attacker jumped off the back of a scooter, pulled out the weapon and chased after the victim and his friends, the jury heard.
He was stabbed repeatedly after tripping and falling. The cause of his death was shock and haemorrhage due to a stab wound to the chest, police said.
The Metropolitan Police has issued guidance about 'zombie' knives, advising that this is how certain ornate knives are currently being marketed. The force says:
Children were playing in the park at the time of the attack.
As the killer was ridden from the scene, the court heard he shouted out "RP" - standing for Red Pitch, a rival to a gang in the Nightingale Park area.
The alleged getaway rider, 17, was cleared of murder while another boy, also 17, was found not guilty of conspiracy to cause grievous bodily harm.
After the machete attack, the killer fled to Bristol and tried to fly to Malaga in Spain, but was arrested when he returned to London to lie low.
In his defence, the killer said he had come under attack when he went to snatch back his bicycle which had been stolen by another boy.
The court heard he had a previous conviction for possessing a blade after being caught with a lock-knife in a McDonald's restaurant a year before the killing.
Prosecutor Simon Denison QC said Mr Appleton's death was another "tragic waste of a young life" taken by a knife.
Speaking after the conviction, Det Ch Insp Chris Jones said: "There can be absolutely no excuse for young people to carry such dreadful weapons on London's streets and this case once again highlights the awful consequences of doing so."

Lachlan returns to the Murdoch empire as co-chairman of News Corp and 21st Century Fox, having previously stood back to focus on his own businesses.
Meanwhile, younger son James was appointed co-chief operating officer at 21st Century Fox.
After the phone hacking scandal, James quit as executive chairman of News International in 2012.
News Corp is one of the world's biggest media organisations, and owns newspaper titles The Times, Sun, and the Wall Street Journal.
News Corp split from 21st Century Fox in 2013. The business owns broadcaster Fox News in the US and British Sky Broadcasting in the UK.
Rupert Murdoch, who went through a high-profile split with wife Wendi Deng last year, said Lachlan was a "talented executive" with a "rich" knowledge of the business.
Lachlan will report to Chase Carey, chief executive at 21st Century Fox.
Rupert said: "I am very pleased he is returning to a leadership role at the company, where he will look closely with me, Chase, James and rest of the board of directors to drive continued growth for years to come."
He also said he was "pleased" to promote James into the "important role".
There is reportedly no new role for the third sibling, Elisabeth Murdoch, however, who sought to distance herself from James after the phone hacking scandal.

BBC Africa noted that by 16:36 BST on October 6, 2016, over 500 South African students were involved in national demonstrations opposing higher university tuition, building on a movement initiated earlier that month.

The Caerau hill fort near Ely is thought to have been occupied from the 5th Century BC by the Silurian tribe.
A dig last year involving 1,000 people found its use may have continued into the late Roman era or even later.
The Caerau And Ely Rediscovering Heritage (Caer) Project runs until 25 July.
Organisers say work on the site since 2011 has helped rewrite the history of early Cardiff, revealing an early occupation date for a hill fort with "massive" ramparts.
Last year's excavations revealed:
Caer Heritage Project co-director Olly Davis said: "During the 2013 dig, more than 1,000 local people visited the dig while it was happening, and 120 more were directly involved in the archaeological work.
"Our challenge this year is to attract twice as many visitors and to get the people of South Wales to value this amazing site and celebrate the remarkable communities which live in its shadow."

Up to 40,000 people and 140 bands took part in the march, which is the largest loyal order demonstration in Northern Ireland.
Three people have been arrested for public order offences.
The event began with a parade around the city's historic walls and was followed by a wreath laying ceremony at the War Memorial in the Diamond.
A religious service was also held in St Columb's Cathedral.
PSNI Supt Mark McEwan praised all sides for working together to ensure the parade was peaceful.
"There haven't been any problems today at all, the operation has been a success," he said.
"Everyone seems to have been enjoying a good day out. The feeling and atmosphere in the city is one of festivity."
Jim Brownlee, governor of the Apprentice Boys of Derry, said the emphasis within the Apprentice Boys was on respect.
"That's still down to every member of this association especially when we're on parade and in the public domain," he said.
"We want people to respect this parade and we want the people on parade to respect the people who will either be watching it or commenting upon it."
A pageant re-enacting the Siege of Derry took place ahead of the start of the main parade.

Armed troops are already being deployed to protect key locations such as Buckingham Palace, Downing Street and embassies to free up police officers.
It comes after the bomb attack at Manchester Arena on Monday which killed 22 people, some as young as eight.
London mayor Sadiq Khan said security experts were advising event organisers.
He said there was "no reason to be alarmed or to panic, this is a prudent course to take".
Bomber 'likely' not acting alone
Manchester attack: The next steps for police and MI5
The mayor added he was in close contact with Met Police Commissioner Cressida Dick and the force had assured him they have all the resources they need.
The decision to replace police officers with soldiers at key public locations was taken at a meeting of the government's emergency Cobra committee on Tuesday.
After the announcement the national security threat level was raised to critical and the Palace of Westminster shut to the public.
All tours and events due to take place there have been cancelled with immediate effect.
A man with a knife was arrested outside Buckingham Palace earlier, shortly before the Queen was driven along the Mall. The Met has said the incident is not terror-related.
The FA Cup final between Arsenal and Chelsea takes place at Wembley on Saturday - the final day of the Chelsea Flower Show.
Commander Jane Connors, leading the London policing operation, said: "We will do all we can to protect the capital at this unsettling time. All our work is designed to make our city as hostile an environment as possible for terrorists to plan and operate."
Other measures being taken include an increase in armed officers to provide support for uniformed and undercover officers trying to spot people carrying out "hostile reconnaissance" and other criminal activity in London.
The tactic is "based on extensive research into the psychology of criminals and what undermines their activities", the force said.
There will also be an increase in the use of stop and search, vehicle check points and number plate recognition technology.
"The reality is we must be prepared to be able to respond to and deal with armed and deadly attackers, so we must be in a position to respond with firearms officers who will use force to stop those attackers in their aim," added Ms Connors.

In 2014, Kim Lennon said the smuggling of drugs was rife at Lewes Prison and its wings "resembled a war zone".
She was dismissed earlier this week following disciplinary proceedings but said she would appeal and had no regrets about speaking out.
The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) said Ms Lennon was not dismissed for being a whistleblower.
'Insufficient staff'
Ms Lennon alleged in August 2014 that the drug Spice was being smuggled into the jail.
She said officers were supposed to carry out daily cell checks but there were insufficient staff to do so, and that she feared an inmate or prison officer would be seriously injured.
The Prison Service denied at the time that staffing levels were unsafe and said there was a "zero-tolerance approach" to illicit substances.
Ms Lennon was suspended from her job after talking to the The Argus newspaper and the BBC.
"Speaking out has caused me a lot of distress but I don't regret it," she said. "Frontline prison officers are too afraid to speak out because of what will happen to them."
"I loved my job and I feel like I am being punished for doing the right thing," she said.
"I am going to appeal but I'm taking it one day at a time."
The MoJ said it could not comment because Ms Lennon's dismissal was a confidential matter.
"We would not wish to prejudice a possible appeal," it said in a statement, adding it took the issue of staff discipline extremely seriously.
"Any unprofessional behaviour will be investigated immediately, with strong action taken and serious wrongdoing referred to the police," it said.
"Disciplinary action can range from a verbal warning to dismissal from their post."

That is according to new figures from Northern Ireland Screen, which has provided production funding for the HBO series.
The programme, some of which is filmed in Northern Ireland, has been nominated for 24 Emmy awards.
Two of those nominations are for Northern Ireland production crew members.
Ronan Hill, who won an Emmy in 2012, has been nominated again for outstanding sound mixing for a drama, while Carla Stronge has been nominated for outstanding casting for a drama.
Northern Ireland Screen has invested ¬£12.45m in the series since it began in 2010.
For that investment, it is estimated that ¬£110.7m has been spent on goods and services in the Northern Ireland economy.
From 2010-14, Game of Thrones brought in between ¬£21m and ¬£23m a year to Northern Ireland. Those figures have been audited.
In 2014-15, in which series five of Game of Thrones was filmed, NI Screen invested ¬£1.6m in the programme, and the return that created is estimated at ¬£22m.
Game of Thrones is filmed at the Titanic Studios in Belfast, and many other locations across Northern Ireland.
Many local companies are involved in providing services when the series is in production, and sites from the show have become tourist attractions.
Damian Carr, from Game of Thrones Tours, said fans come from all over the world to visit the filming locations.
"We've had people from North and South America, all over Asia - China, Japan, Korea, Taiwan - and all across Europe.
"We started off running one tour a week; now we're running five."
Richard Williams, chief executive of NI Screen, said Game of Thrones had established Northern Ireland as a world-class location for film and TV production.
"Additionally, films and television programmes have a significant, positive effect on tourism; they contribute to a wider 'branding' of people, society and culture, all of which has a very strong influence on creating a desire to travel.
"There is no doubt that Game of Thrones is spearheading this set-jetting phenomenon and we have made no secret of the fact that we hope the show will do for Northern Ireland what Lord of the Rings did for New Zealand," he said.

The suspects are accused of smuggling large quantities of cocaine from Colombia to Europe in sailing boats.
Officials said among those arrested is a commander of the Colombian left-wing rebel group, Farc.
Police said the suspects were part of a transatlantic drugs ring run by the 'Ndrangheta crime syndicate, which has its base in southern Italy.
The investigation, dubbed Santa Fe, was carried out jointly by Italian agents, members of the US Drug Enforcement Administration and Spain's Guardia Civil.
Officials said the drug ring operated in countries as far flung as Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Spain and Montenegro.
The identity of the Farc commander has not yet been made public, but Colombian media said it would soon be revealed.
The rebel group derives much of its finances from cocaine production and trafficking.
Officials said that in the course of their investigations they seized a total of four tonnes of cocaine.
One of the largest seizures was in the night of 25-26 August last year when the Spanish navy stopped a sailboat heading for the Italian coast.
They found 856kg of cocaine on board.
They said that the drugs were smuggled from Colombia mainly into southern Italian port of Gioia Tauro in Calabria, but that they were also taken to ports in northern Italy such as Vado Ligure, Livorno and Genoa.
Police say the 'Ndrangheta operates the biggest cocaine smuggling network in Europe.

A black Ford Fiesta, making a sharp turn from Lugsmore Lane onto Dunriding Lane, unexpectedly hit two pedestrians: a young girl and a 55-year-old woman. The older woman was knocked to the ground, while the girl managed to leap aside, narrowly escaping serious harm. Emergency services promptly arrived at the scene.

A report has said uniting council departments with different responsibilities would help improve the town's prospects.
The strategy aims to reduce the number of empty shop units, increase visitors with more public events and reduce antisocial behaviour.
It is being discussed at a council meeting on Wednesday afternoon.
Town centre forum business group chairman Andrew Atkinson welcomed the report and said it could lead to be a "huge turnaround for Wrexham".
The report highlights how one department looks after town centre economic strategy while others deal with cleaning up the streets or looking after licensing and public protection issues although they share a common goal.
It recommends a single group taking forward all issues that tackle town centre improvements.
Mr Atkinson said: "It has got to be action and not words from the council."
He said the authority was taking positive steps with shops' vacancy rates reducing due to more independent shops opening, but he admitted bigger units formerly occupied by multi national firms were "harder to fill".
This month, work started on a ¬£4.5m development at Wrexham's People's Market to incorporate an arts centre.

The statement from the firm came just days after it announced the sale of the Financial Times to Japan's Nikkei.
Pearson said it was in discussions regarding the sale of the Economist but there was "no certainty that this process will lead to a transaction".
It did not name the potential buyers, but Italy's Agnelli family said it was in talks to increase its holding.
Exor, the investment arm of the Agnelli family, currently holds a 4.72% stake in the Economist Group.
The firm said on its website that any increased investment would "represent a minority shareholding in the the Economist... reflecting Exor's strong commitment to the editorial independence that lies at the heart of the Economist's ethos and success".
It also stressed that there was no certainty of a deal.
Other Economist shareholders include the family dynasties Cadbury, Rothschild and Schroder.
The Financial Times reported that the 50% stake was valued at √Ç¬£400m and that the sale was likely to be concluded over the summer.
The Economist Group includes in the Economist magazine, the research company the Economist Intelligence Unit and the US legislative information provider CQ Roll Call.
On Thursday Pearson agreed to sell the Financial Times for √Ç¬£844m as part of the group's strategy to focus just on education.

Zdenko Turtak, who was extradited from Slovakia, had previously admitted rape and grievous bodily harm.
Turtak attacked his victim at a bus stop in Beeston Road in March before dragging her behind a hedge and raping her. He later fled the UK.
He will be sentenced on 19 October at Leeds Crown Court.
Prosecutors did not to pursue the attempted murder charge at Leeds Crown Court on Thursday.

The star of How I Met Your Mother and Gone Girl will host 10 episodes of the variety show for NBC, according to the Hollywood Reporter.
Harris called the show, created by British TV presenting duo Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly, "a game changer".
McPartlin, Donnelly and Harris will produce the yet-to-be named show, which is likely not to air on Saturdays.
The show, which pays homage to variety shows of the past, started in the UK in 2002.
It won two Bafta awards this year and there are versions in Germany, Portugal, Italy and Belgium.
The show features comedy sketches, song and dance numbers and audience interaction.
"As I watched the show, I couldn't stop smiling. Now that I've seen many seasons, my face hurts," Harris said.
"Its unique structure fits right into my random skill set. I can't wait to roll up my sleeves and have some fun."
Harris has just finished a run on Broadway in Hedwig and the Angry Inch and was recently announced as the host of the 2015 Oscars.
Last year he made his fourth appearance hosting the Tony Awards, drawing plaudits for his hosting duties and show-stopping opening number.

The 24-year-old, who cannot be named until he enters his plea, is accused of raping the teenager in the toilets of a bar in Johannesburg.
Earlier in the week, the family of the alleged victim said that Mr Mandela's ex-wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, had sent her bodyguard to dissuade them from pressing charges.
The Mandela family has not commented.
Senior members of the Mandela family, including the former president's daughter Makaziwe Mandela, were in court during a brief hearing.
His bail application has been postponed until Tuesday, meaning he cannot legally be named until then.
He has been in custody since his arrest on Saturday.
The BBC understands that he will argue that it was consensual sex and he didn't know that his accuser was underage since the pub did not allow under-21s on its premises.
Under South African law, sex with someone under 16 is classed as rape whether consensual or not.
BBC Southern Africa correspondent Karen Allen says the family of South Africa's first black president have found themselves constantly in the public spotlight.
Just three months ago, another of his grandsons, Mandla Mandela, was given a suspended sentence after being convicted of assault, following an attack on a teacher after a road rage incident.

Members of Braintree's Dolphin Women's Institute (WI) have stitched some of the town's best-known landmarks including the church and museum.
Each model is about 45cm (18in) tall and was created using a polystyrene or cardboard core with knitting sewn on.
It took nine knitters seven months to complete the seven miniature buildings which will be displayed at the town's museum next month.
The group's vice-president, Elaine Pye, said the project was inspired by a similar one a relative had been involved in knitting in Hertfordshire.
"They knitted their own cottages, but we couldn't really do that so chose some of the town's beautiful iconic buildings," she said.
Mrs Pye put together the polystyrene structures and each knitter got to work, returning after two weeks with their latest knitted piece of church spire or pub frontage.
After much gluing, sewing and additional knitted embellishments, the town finally took shape, brought together with mini woollen market stalls.
The group created models of the town hall, church, Swan pub, library, museum, shopping centre and even the railway station complete with knitted train.
"It really brought everyone together and the response has been amazing," Mrs Pye said.
"So much so that they want to do more, so we think we might knit the Public Gardens next."

A total of 374 employees lost their jobs when Tullis Russell Papermakers, based at Markinch in Fife, went into administration in April 2015.
Each employee received the equivalent of eight weeks' wages in compensation for their loss.
The award follows a judgement from an employment tribunal in Dundee.
Lawyers said that despite the company directors being under an obligation to provide employees with at least 45 days' notice - as more than 100 workers were losing their jobs - this was ignored, meaning each employee was entitled to sue for compensation.
However, acting alone would have meant each affected worker lodging "an extremely complex" and expensive employment tribunal claim, so they made a joint bid.
David Martyn, a senior employment lawyer at Thompsons, the firm that represented the workers, said: "The more notice the workforce have to prepare for these devastating changes, the better they can organise their financial responsibilities to soften the blow.
"This award of compensation will be paid by UK administration service.
"That means that the taxpayer has picked up the tab because company directors have played fast and loose with the rules.
"This has to stop and I believe we need to see more criminal prosecutions of companies that behave this way."
Paul Reilly, Unite branch secretary said: "This is a great result for my members and it goes a long way towards the hurt that happened."

The move follows a rise in the number of oil and gas operators using unmanned aerial systems (UAS) to conduct inspections and other offshore tasks.
The guidelines were developed by industry and aviation safety experts and UAS operators.
They cover best practice, procedures and the certification needed to be compliant with UAS regulations.
Oil and Gas UK's health, safety and environment director Mick Borwell said: "A small but increasing number of oil and gas operators are using UAS for inspections predominantly, but also for aerial photography, surveying and security.
"The technology is particularly attractive for its use in improving safety.
"For example, sending unmanned aircraft instead of people into confined spaces to conduct inspections reduces risk, and is also effective and efficient.
"We expect their usage to grow."
Mr Borwell said the new guidelines aimed to be consistent with safety and operating standards already adopted on the UK Continental Shelf for offshore oil and gas production and helicopter flight operations.
He added: "The intention is to encourage offshore operators planning on using this emerging technology to think about the whole operating and safety system offshore and not just the air vehicle."

Powell, 21, featured 16 times last year and played in the season opener loss to Huddersfield, and a warm-up match against New Zealand Warriors.
"It is a big blow for Sam, who has worked really hard in pre-season," said head coach Shaun Wane.
"But with his character I'm sure he will bounce back stronger."
The full extent of Powell's injury will be assessed when Warriors return home after the game in Sydney.

Ronnie Howard, 31, died following a disturbance at the Prince Edward in South Shields, on 1 May.
At Newcastle Crown Court Michael Wilson, 35, of of Hylton Avenue, South Shields, appeared by video link from Durham Prison to deny the charge.
A trial date was set for 4 October and Mr Wilson was remanded in custody. Four other men have denied offences including assault and affray.

Proposed deep cuts to the council's animal welfare service could force it to concentrate solely on its mandatory duties of taking in and housing stray dogs. This drastic proposition, up for discussion at the February council meeting, has generated widespread apprehension. Opponents fear such reductions would gravely compromise the unit's proactive programs, impeding its efforts to address animal mistreatment, perform welfare assessments, and offer essential community support. The team's priority would shift from holistic animal care to a basic, reactive capacity, mainly dealing with abandoned animals and critical situations. In essence, this significant defunding could intensify local animal suffering.

Kathryn Smith admitted to allocating a portion of her £52 weekly state benefits to purchase Class B drugs. Jurors were previously informed of her apprehension that her 21-month-old daughter, Ayeeshia Jane Smith, might have suffered a seizure after ingesting illegal substances found within their home. Both Ms. Smith and her former partner, Matthew Rigby, deny murder charges. The young victim, known as AJ, tragically died in 2014 at the family's residence on St Giles Road, Burton-upon-Trent, following what the prosecution described as a "terrible assault." The court heard that AJ sustained "catastrophic" injuries, including a lacerated heart and internal bleeding, consistent with a powerful physical impact. Post-mortem examinations also revealed evidence of prior injuries, such as an earlier brain bleed and fractured ribs, suggesting she had endured non-accidental harm on multiple occasions before her death.

During the prosecution's opening statement, Christopher Hotten QC told the jury that Ms. Smith, 23, and Matthew Rigby, 21, were jointly responsible for the fatal injuries inflicted upon AJ. He alleged that the couple, known for their tumultuous relationship, either conspired to cause serious harm or that one inflicted the injuries while the other failed to protect the child. Evidence presented depicted a chaotic living environment where drug use, including cannabis, was widespread. Ms. Smith's confession about using her limited welfare funds for drug purchases underscored the challenging conditions in which AJ lived. The prosecution further highlighted text messages and phone calls exchanged between Ms. Smith and Rigby in the hours leading up to AJ's death, which conveyed escalating tension and anxiety regarding AJ's health, specifically concerns that she might have consumed drugs.

Under cross-examination, Ms. Smith maintained her innocence, accusing Matthew Rigby of being the perpetrator of the fatal injuries. She claimed to have briefly left the room, only to return and find AJ unresponsive. Conversely, Rigby's defence team asserted Ms. Smith's culpability, suggesting she had a history of losing her temper and acting violently. The court heard contradictory statements from both defendants, each attempting to shift the blame to the other. Social services had been involved with the family before AJ's death, with welfare concerns for the child repeatedly documented. Records of these interventions and assessments were presented as evidence. The trial, presided over by Mr. Justice Haddon-Cave at Stafford Crown Court, continues as medical experts, police officers, and other witnesses involved in the investigation provide testimony. The jury's responsibility is to determine who was accountable for Ayeeshia Jane Smith's tragic demise, considering the intricate web of evidence and the opposing narratives presented by the defence and prosecution. The deeply distressing nature of this case, involving a very young child, has drawn considerable public attention to the proceedings.

The four bedroom Georgian home provided the setting where eight-year-old Kevin McCallister, played by Macauley Culkin, outwitted a pair of bungling burglers.
The film earned more than $477m (¬£291m) at the box office and spawned a number of sequels.
Owners John and Cynthia Abendshien lived in the house during filming.
They said they had been approached by producer John Hughes' company about using their property in Winnetka, Illinois as a set for his previous film Uncle Buck, but had refused.
When a location scout returned 18 months later for Home Alone, they agreed to turn their 1920s built home into a movie set.
Mr Abendshien described the film's child star Culkin as "a nice, but quiet young boy".
The film was directed by Christopher Columbus, who went on to direct two of the Harry Potter films and Percy Jackson & the Lightning Thief.
Producer Hughes - a prolific director in the 1980s - died of a heart attack two years ago.

Hank Costain, 88, from Charminster, near Dorchester, first flew a Spitfire in 1942, at the age of 19.
The maiden flight of the Supermarine Spitfire took place on 5 March 1936, from Eastleigh Aerodrome, now Southampton Airport.
Mr Costain described flying a Spitfire as "absolutely marvellous".
He said: "When you first got into the seat and opened the throttle it felt as if someone had given you a good kick up the bottom and away you went.
"It would do everything you asked of it. Compared to other aircraft it was light on the controls, you could do all the aerobatics and you would come up to speed very quickly.
"If you treated a Spitfire properly, it treated you properly. Treat it roughly or be careless with it and you were in trouble, in that it would do all sorts of things such as ground looping. It also had a very fragile undercarriage and could collapse."
Mr Costain was a member of the RAF for 37 years.
He flew operational Spitfires over Europe, north Africa, the Middle East and Burma.
He was also a Spitfire instructor during that time and became a test pilot on Spitfires at 9MU Cosford, Shropshire.
He said: "Everyone that joined the air force wanted to fly a Spitfire.
"I would say that I have flown nearly all of the operational Spitfires.
"There aren't many of us left [alive] that have flown the number of different marks of Spitfire that I have."
During and since his flying days, Mr Costain says he has often been asked if he was frightened during the war years.
He said: "I was terrified, but I was terrified of letting my own friends see that I was frightened. One made one's self very determined that you wouldn't show that.
"If you were attacked when you were flying a Spitfire during the war years, you turned hard into the attacking aircraft and they just couldn't get behind you! It was much more manoeuvrable than the German aircraft.
"I don't think we should ever forget what the Spitfire did for England. It was virtually England's saving grace."

As many as 23 civilians were killed in the raid on a village in Yakla district on Saturday, including 10 children, rights group Reprieve says.
Yemeni reports say the victims included the daughter of Anwar al-Awlaki, a militant killed by a US strike in 2011.
The raid was the first such operation authorised by President Donald Trump.
The US military had previously said a Navy Seal, William "Ryan" Owens, 36, died and three others were injured. But the US Central Command (Centcom) later said that those killed could include children.
Several Apache helicopters were reported to have taken part in the operation, which killed 14 militants, including three al-Qaeda leaders, according to the US military.
White House spokesman Sean Spicer told journalists: "It's hard to ever call something a complete success when you have a loss of life or people injured."
"But I think when you look at the totality of what was gained to prevent the future loss of life... I think it's a successful operation in all standards."
He made no mention of civilian victims.
Earlier on Thursday, Reprieve said a newborn baby was among 10 children killed in the attack.
It also cited local reports as saying that a heavily pregnant woman was shot in the stomach during the raid and subsequently gave birth to an injured baby boy who later died.
Images of several dead children emerged on social media soon after the attack took place.
Earlier this week, Pentagon spokesman Capt Jeff Davis told reporters to "take reports of female casualties with a grain of salt", adding that they had been "trained to be ready and trained to be combatants".
But US military Central Command on Wednesday acknowledged that a number of civilians had been "likely killed in the midst of a firefight".
Mr Trump travelled to Dover Air Force Base in Delaware on Thursday to receive the body of the US Navy Seal, William 'Ryan' Owens, who was killed in the raid.
Al-Qaeda has taken advantage of the civil war in Yemen to entrench its presence in the south and south-east of the country.
For the past two years, Yemen has been embroiled in fighting between forces loyal to the internationally recognised president, backed by a Saudi-led coalition, and Shia Houthi rebels.

Burnley wasted no time in establishing an early lead, with Jay Rodriguez heading home from close range after just three minutes, following an exquisite cross from Kieran Trippier. Despite later missing a penalty, awarded when Ben Mee was fouled by Garath McCleary, Rodriguez quickly added his second goal, once again connecting with a superb delivery from Trippier. For the visiting side, Wolves, Adlene Guedioura came closest to finding the net, rattling the crossbar with a powerful long-range strike early in the second half. However, despite their persistent efforts, Wolves found it challenging to penetrate Burnley's well-organized and formidable defence, expertly marshaled by Ben Mee. Buoyed by Rodriguez’s brace, the home team commanded significant possession in midfield, with Trippier consistently posing a threat on the right flank, his dangerous crosses causing continuous problems for the opposition.

Burnley’s clear dominance persisted as they aggressively pressed for a third goal to definitively secure their victory. Scott Arfield and George Boyd were effective on the wings, creating vital space for their full-backs to join the attack. Trippier, notably, seemed to be delivering one of his most influential performances of the season, his precise crosses repeatedly unsettling the Wolves penalty area. Nevertheless, Wolves’ goalkeeper Carl Ikeme made several crucial interventions, including an outstanding save from a fierce Rodriguez volley that would have completed his hat-trick and further extended Burnley’s advantage.

As the match approached its conclusion, Wolves pushed further up the pitch, desperate to score a goal that might reignite their hopes. Garath McCleary, who had been involved in the earlier penalty incident, attempted to make amends with several incisive runs, but his efforts often lacked adequate support. Burnley’s defensive line, anchored by Ben Mee, remained steadfast against the late pressure. Manager Sean Dyche responded with tactical substitutions, bringing on fresh players to reinforce the midfield and defence, thereby maintaining their high work rate. The game ended with Burnley securing a comfortable 2-0 win, a scoreline that accurately reflected their superior attacking prowess and defensive stability. Jay Rodriguez’s clinical finishing, coupled with Kieran Trippier’s exceptional supply of balls, proved to be the decisive factors in a commanding display by the Clarets. This victory propelled Burnley further up the Championship standings, solidifying their position as strong contenders for promotion. Meanwhile, Wolves were left to lament a squandered opportunity away from home.

West Ham United is reportedly preparing an enhanced bid for striker Jermain Defoe, who began his professional football career at the east London club. The 34-year-old forward has been exceptionally effective for struggling Premier League side Sunderland this season, netting 11 goals in 21 appearances. His impressive recent form was clearly demonstrated on Monday when he successfully converted two penalties, allowing Sunderland to recover twice from a deficit and secure a 2-2 draw against Liverpool at the Stadium of Light. These vital goals underscored his consistent quality and pivotal role in David Moyes' team, which is battling to avoid relegation.

Despite their precarious position in the Premier League standings, Sunderland steadfastly asserts that Defoe is not available for transfer. Manager Moyes has frequently stated that selling such a prolific forward, a crucial component of their attacking strategy, would severely jeopardise their chances of remaining in the top flight.

Nevertheless, West Ham's pursuit of the player remains strong. Manager Slaven Bilic is eager to acquire an experienced goalscorer, as the Hammers have contended with inconsistent scoring and numerous player injuries throughout the current campaign. Bringing in a player with Defoe's proven talent and extensive Premier League experience is viewed as a critical step to bolster their aspirations at the London Stadium. The improved offer from the east London club is understood to be around £6 million, but Sunderland reportedly values him significantly higher, closer to £10-12 million, emphasizing his irreplaceable worth.

Defoe, meanwhile, maintains his complete dedication to his on-pitch responsibilities, showing unwavering loyalty to the Black Cats. His primary objective is unequivocally to help Sunderland retain their Premier League status, a formidable challenge in which he has been a leading figure. This transfer saga is anticipated to continue until the window closes, with West Ham likely to intensify their efforts to sign Defoe, even as Sunderland remains resolute in its 'not for sale' stance regarding their indispensable forward.

In a crucial Italian rugby game, Treviso's scrum-half, Senioli, prematurely celebrated a seemingly certain try near the line by smirking and gesturing at Scarlets' Scott Williams. However, this assured score was spectacularly thwarted by the Welsh international, Scott Williams, celebrated for his unyielding defense and fierce resolve, who launched into a last-ditch diving tackle. The roar of the fervent Treviso home crowd was abruptly hushed as Williams, against all odds, snagged Senioli's ankle just a few inches from the whitewash. This tackle sent Senioli sprawling, breaking his momentum and forcing him to drop the ball he had been casually holding, expecting a simple touchdown. The ball then bounced precariously close to the line until a Scarlets forward, though a fraction late, seized the opportunity to recover it, gaining crucial possession. A collective groan from the Italian faithful was immediately countered by a wave of relief from the small contingent of visiting Welsh fans. Senioli, still grounded, stared up in pure disbelief, his earlier swagger dissolved into deep frustration. Scott Williams, quickly upright, offered a subtle nod, acknowledging the fierce cross-border rivalry. This pivotal intervention, a testament to Williams's immense tenacity, dramatically altered the course of the match. Treviso, previously dominant, now appeared shaken, while Scarlets, buoyed by the exceptional defensive play, discovered renewed vigor. The encounter, vital for both teams' European aspirations, hung in the balance, highlighting the intense rugby rivalry between Italy and Wales.

The 24-year-old was playing his fourth game since joining the Dons in August after leaving Championship side Leeds.
But after a collision in the game, the former Manchester United youngster will see a surgeon next week.
Dons boss Karl Robinson said the club was "gutted" for Wootton.
"Despite only being with us for a short time, Scott has made a big impression both on and off the pitch," Robinson told the club website.
"He's a leader and well liked by everyone so this is a difficult one to take, but knowing Scott like I do, he'll come back even bigger and better than before."

Writing in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing, clinicians say there is a growing trend for under-25s to seek the wrinkle-smoothing injections.
But the research suggests "frozen faces" could stop young people from learning how to express emotions fully.
A leading body of UK plastic surgeons says injecting teenagers for cosmetic reasons is "morally wrong".
Botox and other versions of the toxin work by temporarily paralysing muscles in the upper face to reduce wrinkling when people frown.
Nurse practitioner Helen Collier, who carried out the research, says reality TV shows and celebrity culture are driving young people to idealise the  "inexpressive frozen face."
But she points to a well-known psychological theory, the facial feedback hypothesis, that suggests adolescents learn how best to relate to people by mimicking their facial expressions.
She says: "As a human being our ability to demonstrate a wide range of emotions is very dependent on facial expressions.
"Emotions such as empathy and sympathy help us to survive and grow into confident and communicative adults."
But she warns that a "growing generation of blank-faced" young people could be harming their ability to correctly convey their feelings.
"If you wipe those expressions out, this might stunt their emotional and social development," she says.
The research calls for practitioners to use assessment tools to decide whether there are clear clinical reasons for Botox treatment.
Several assessment scales exist that take into account how thick the skin is, how sun-damaged it appears, and the depth of any wrinkles, but experts warn that some Botox clinics are putting financial gain first.
Ms Collier calls on therapists to spend time helping young people boost their confidence rather than reaching for injections.
She adds: "Though most of the effects of the toxin are temporary, research suggests the muscles don't fully recover from injections.
"We really need to understand the consequences of starting treatments too soon."
Dr Michael Lewis, a researcher in psychology at Cardiff University, says: "The expressions we make on our face affect the emotions we feel.
"We smile because we are happy, but smiling also makes us happy.
"Treatment with drugs like Botox prevents the patient from being able to make a particular expression and can therefore have an effect on our learning to feel emotions naturally."
Rajiv Grover, president of the British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons, says: "Injecting teenagers with Botox for cosmetic purposes is morally wrong and something that no ethical practitioner would do.
"This can only exacerbate body image issues at a vulnerable time."
Ms Collier's research will be presented at the Clinical Cosmetic and Reconstructive Expo in October.

When British archaeologist Howard Carter unearthed two daggers from the burial attire of the young pharaoh Tutankhamun in 1925, one immediately stood out due to its extraordinarily well-preserved iron blade. The fact that this blade remained uncorroded, despite being over 3,300 years old since Tutankhamun's mummification, and considering the general scarcity of iron artifacts in ancient Egypt, had long baffled experts. However, a recent collaborative effort by Italian and Egyptian researchers utilized a non-invasive X-ray technique to confirm its extraterrestrial origin, most likely from a meteorite. The findings, detailed in *Meteoritics and Planetary Science*, revealed the blade's unique chemical composition, particularly its high concentrations of nickel and cobalt—elements characteristic of iron meteorites but seldom found in terrestrial iron. This significant discovery finally provided a definitive answer to a profound archaeological mystery that had intrigued academics since its initial finding in Tutankhamun's tomb.

Specialists from Milan's Polytechnic University and the Egyptian Museum in Cairo further substantiated the blade's celestial source through advanced X-ray fluorescence analysis. The crucial piece of evidence was the notably high level of nickel, an element rarely present in such abundance in iron extracted from Earthly mines. This finding suggests that ancient Egyptian metalworkers, despite their renowned skill with gold and copper, were able to identify and skillfully work with this distinct "sky-metal" that had fallen from space. Furthermore, the dagger's remarkable resilience to degradation over three millennia lends additional credence to its extraterrestrial origins, as meteoric iron often exhibits superior durability owing to its distinct crystalline structure and elemental makeup.

This discovery offers considerable new perspectives on the technological capabilities and available materials during Egypt's New Kingdom era. It implies that ancient Egyptians recognized and valued "sky-iron" and possessed the advanced craftsmanship necessary to forge it into sophisticated, precious objects fitting for a pharaoh like Tutankhamun. A material directly from the cosmos would undoubtedly have carried profound cultural and symbolic significance, greatly enhancing the young king's prestige and authority. Interestingly, the accompanying dagger was crafted from gold, providing a stark contrast to the 'heavenly' iron piece and emphasizing the iron blade's unique and potentially sacred standing. This research powerfully demonstrates how an interdisciplinary approach—integrating archaeology, art history, and modern scientific analysis—can unlock unparalleled understandings of Tutankhamun's epoch and civilization.

UK lawmakers have formally approved the nation's departure from the European Union for the first time, with its start slated for late March. The government's chief whip clearly showed satisfaction after the evening's vote. Ministers strategically convinced Labour to endorse the Article 50 activation timetable, making a shrewd concession without major demands in return. This concession was a government promise to issue a Brexit white paper and allow parliamentary debate on the negotiation strategy before Article 50 is triggered. This tactical move gave crucial political leverage to Labour MPs, particularly those representing pro-Remain constituencies. It allowed them to support the schedule, presenting their backing as a push for parliamentary scrutiny rather than simply bowing to Theresa May's agenda. This helped them reassure concerned voters and avoid accusations of obstructing the democratic will.

This legislative triumph carries immense weight for Theresa May. It considerably strengthens her authority over the Brexit process, showcasing her capacity to secure a House of Commons majority for her chosen timeline. The chief whip's satisfaction suggested a successful navigation of intricate political hurdles, temporarily quieting her critics. This outcome reinforces May's standing for complex negotiations with the EU, bolstering her claim that the UK is united in its determination to leave by the specified deadline. The focus now unequivocally transitions from the procedural aspects of triggering Article 50 to outlining Britain's future relationship with Europe.

However, significant disagreements persist. While Labour's leadership achieved a pragmatic compromise, many within the party and the wider pro-Remain camp remain uneasy. The white paper offers only limited true legislative authority over the final Brexit terms. Voices from the Remain camp are expected to grow louder as the immense intricacies of detaching from the EU become clearer, especially concerning single market and customs union access. The upcoming months will rigorously test the government’s resolve and internal cohesion as Brexit’s full ramifications come to light. This vote merely concludes the initial phase, ushering in the far more demanding stage of withdrawal and negotiation.
